00:29:14.464 --> 00:29:18.284
for this award, but also for giving me the opportunity to talk

462
00:29:18.324 --> 00:29:22.104
today about my main post-doctoral project, in which I

463
00:29:22.164 --> 00:29:24.594
identify a transcription factor named BMAL2

464
00:29:25.544 --> 00:29:29.024
as a linker between KRAS and hypoxia, and is also involved in

465
00:29:29.064 --> 00:29:31.924
epithelial-mesenchymal transition in pancreatic cancer.

466
00:29:32.944 --> 00:29:36.744
We have no disclosures. Pancreatic cancer is one of the most

467
00:29:36.964 --> 00:29:40.624
lethal disease, particularly because by the time of diagnose, the vast

468
00:29:40.664 --> 00:29:43.924
majority of the patients present an advanced disease, including metastasis.

469
00:29:44.804 --> 00:29:48.684
KRAS is an important driver here. Nearly all patients

470
00:29:48.744 --> 00:29:52.424
have an activating mutations in the KRAS oncogene, which leads to the tumor

471
00:29:52.484 --> 00:29:54.944
initiation and is also involved in tumor evolution.

472
00:29:55.764 --> 00:29:59.604
This is a highly heterogeneous disease and is one of the most, if not the most

473
00:29:59.684 --> 00:30:01.264
hypoxic tumors that we have.

474
00:30:02.264 --> 00:30:04.374
So one of the questions that I had when I joined Dr.

475
00:30:04.864 --> 00:30:08.684
Ken Olive's laboratory was to see whether there were other players involved

476
00:30:08.764 --> 00:30:12.600
in this pancreatic cancer malignancy and evolution.And in order to

477
00:30:12.620 --> 00:30:14.760
answer this question, we first define

478
00:30:15.720 --> 00:30:19.400
key phenotypes important in this event.

479
00:30:19.600 --> 00:30:23.280
The first one will be this tumor initiation, the transition between the

480
00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:26.980
benign precursor spanning IPMN and the actual carcinoma.

481
00:30:27.820 --> 00:30:31.560
We also have tumor progression within the pancreatic carcinoma we have

482
00:30:31.780 --> 00:30:35.620
from low grade to high grade. The association with survival, as well as the

483
00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:39.400
association with the KRAS activity, are also important events to be considered

484
00:30:39.460 --> 00:30:43.400
here. So in order to answer this question, we employ

485
00:30:43.410 --> 00:30:47.320
a systems biology approach called regulatory network

486
00:30:47.380 --> 00:30:51.340
analysis, where we use RNA sequencing profiles

487
00:30:51.420 --> 00:30:55.120
that can help us to measure the activity of regulatory

488
00:30:55.160 --> 00:30:59.000
proteins, transcription factors, co-transcription factors, proteins

489
00:30:59.100 --> 00:31:00.620
that regulate other genes.

490
00:31:01.820 --> 00:31:05.480
Let's imagine for a second that our genome is an orchestra.

491
00:31:05.940 --> 00:31:09.380
The musicians are the genes. They have their

492
00:31:09.500 --> 00:31:12.620
own instrument. They play the music.

493
00:31:13.350 --> 00:31:17.140
The transcription factor, the regulatory protein is, in this case, our

494
00:31:17.360 --> 00:31:17.940
conductor.

495
00:31:18.980 --> 00:31:22.900
The challenge here is that sometimes we don't see the conductor, which means

496
00:31:22.910 --> 00:31:26.860
that in our inexpression profile, we perhaps cannot

497
00:31:26.980 --> 00:31:30.260
see a differential expression in a given transcription factor.

498
00:31:30.540 --> 00:31:32.740
But that doesn't mean that it's not active.

499
00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:36.840
So what we can do is we can see how the music is playing.

500
00:31:36.880 --> 00:31:40.160
The music is here, the transcriptional profile. How we do that?

501
00:31:40.400 --> 00:31:42.240
The conductor is making

502
00:31:43.860 --> 00:31:47.640
all the music playing very smoothly, and by the time we hear

503
00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:52.060
a difference in the music, that is because the

504
00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:55.820
conductor has made a move, and all the musicians has

505
00:31:55.960 --> 00:31:59.600
changed in the playing in a very smooth and in a very coordinated way.

506
00:32:00.240 --> 00:32:04.200
And this is what exactly we do using regulatory network analysis.

507
00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:08.560
We created a map that we call a regulon, with a different downstream

508
00:32:08.640 --> 00:32:12.620
target for a given regulatory protein that are regulated either positively or

